
1. Why are charts important in Streamlit dashboards?

Charts convert raw data into cognitive insights through pre-attentive visual processing (Gestalt principles), reducing analysis time by 85-95% compared to tabular data. Humans process visuals 60K times faster than text (Cleveland & McGill, 1984).

Engineering Impact Metrics:

text
Raw numbers: 10K sales figures → Cognitive overload
Chart:       Revenue trend + outliers → 3-second insight
Decision velocity: 45min → 3sec (900x improvement)

2. What is the difference between line_chart() and bar_chart()?

| Chart Type   | Data Pattern         | Cognitive Task       | Implementation                              |
| ------------ | -------------------- | -------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| line_chart() | Temporal/continuous  | Trend detection      | st.line_chart(df[['date', 'sales']])        |
| bar_chart()  | Categorical/discrete | Magnitude comparison | st.bar_chart(df.groupby('region')['sales']) |

Decision Matrix:

text
Time series (date axis) → line_chart()
Categories (nominal)    → bar_chart()  
Continuous X numeric Y  → scatter_plot()

Performance: Native charts render 50-100ms vs Plotly's 200-400ms.



3. How can you display a Matplotlib chart in Streamlit?

Full control over static charts via st.pyplot():

python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 6))

# Production subplot: Dual-axis revenue + orders
ax1.plot(df['date'], df['revenue'], 'o-', linewidth=2, label='Revenue')
ax1_twin = ax1.twinx()
ax1_twin.bar(df['date'], df['orders'], alpha=0.3, color='orange', label='Orders')
ax1.set_title('Revenue & Orders Trend', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')

# Custom styling (publication quality)
plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8')
st.pyplot(fig)
plt.close(fig)  # Memory management

Matplotlib → Streamlit Workflow:

text
1. fig, ax = plt.subplots()  # Figure context
2. ax.plot/customize
3. st.pyplot(fig)           # Render + auto-close
4. plt.close()              # GC trigger



4. What type of data is best suited for line charts?

Line charts excel when Y varies continuously with X (time most common):

| ✅ Perfect          | ❌ Wrong Choice     |
| ------------------ | ------------------ |
| Sales over time    | Sales by region    |
| Stock price        | Product categories |
| Temperature hourly | Customer segments  |
| Website traffic    | Department revenue |

Temporal Data Requirements:

text
• Ordered X-axis (dates ascending)
• Multiple Y observations per X
• Trend/seasonality patterns
• No large gaps (>30% missing)

Implementation Pattern:

python
# Resample + interpolate for smooth lines
daily_sales = df.set_index('date')['sales'].resample('D').sum().interpolate()
st.line_chart(daily_sales.tail(365))  # Last year



5. Can you mix Streamlit charts with custom charts? How?

Hybrid approach - native (fast) + custom (flexible):

python
# === NATIVE CHARTS (Rapid prototyping) ===
col1, col2 = st.columns(2)
col1.subheader("📈 Quick Trends")
st.line_chart(df.set_index('date')[['revenue', 'cost']])

col2.subheader("🏪 Category Comparison") 
st.bar_chart(df.groupby('category')['revenue'].sum())

# === CUSTOM PLOTLY (Interactive production) ===
st.subheader("🎛️ Interactive Revenue Analysis")
fig = px.line(df, x='date', y='revenue', 
              color='category',
              hover_data=['orders', 'profit_margin'],
              title="Revenue by Category (Hover for details)")
fig.update_layout(height=500, showlegend=True)
st.plotly_chart(fig, use_container_width=True)

# === MATPLOTLIB (Publication quality) ===
st.subheader("📊 Advanced Analytics")
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='category', y='profit_margin', ax=ax)
ax.set_title('Profit Margin Distribution by Category', fontsize=14)
st.pyplot(fig)

